This compute the proportion of the first decile directly from the table above:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
weighted.mean(x = table.income$prop_vote[table.income$d1 == 1], w = table.income$share_decile[table.income$d1 == 1]) # d1
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 0.301588
```
:::
:::


Let's try to compute the 3 first decile in a way that can then be put into a for loop or even into a function later


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# for d_i

weighted.mean(x = c(table.income$prop_vote[table.income[,11] == 1]),
              w = c(table.income$share_decile[table.income[,11] == 1])) #d1: take columns 11 (D1) and the values of prop vote and share decile for which D11 == 1
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 0.301588
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
weighted.mean(x = c(table.income$prop_vote[table.income[,12] == 1]),
              w = c(table.income$share_rest[table.income[,11] == 1 & table.income[, 12] == 1],
                    table.income$share_decile[table.income[,11] == 0 & table.income[,12] == 1])) #d2
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 0.2350616
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
weighted.mean(x = c(table.income$prop_vote[table.income[,13] == 1]),
              w = c(table.income$share_rest[table.income[,13-1] == 1 & table.income[, 13] == 1], #d3
                    table.income$share_decile[table.income[13-1] == 0 & table.income[,13] == 1]))
```

